  "text": "The negatively charged dissociated diclofop would move back across the plasmalemma in response to the transplasmalemma electrical gradient. Under the conditions proposed by Wright and Shimabukuro [CITATION_1] , it is reasonable to expect a portion of the diclofop anion in the apoplasm to move with the bulk flow of water in the transpiration stream. Herbicides which readily penetrate the plasmalemma of plant cells, including atrazine (10), nearly always display apoplasmic translocation patterns. However, Brezeanu et al. [CITATION_2] demonstrated that only 4% of the absorbed herbicide translocated away from the point of application 96 h after treatment in wheat and oat leaves. Of that which translocated, much of the movement was through the symplasmic pathway. This suggests that the lipophilic acid ester is rapidly deesterified in the cytoplasm, but once hydrolyzed, exists predominantly as an impermeant anion.",
